value.name: 2MASS - Wikipedia
value.snippet: 2MASS produced an astronomical catalog with over 300 million observed objects, including minor planets of the Solar System, brown dwarfs, low-mass stars, nebulae, star clusters and galaxies. In addition, 1 million objects were cataloged in the 2MASS Extended Source Catalog (2MASX).

value.name: IRSA - Two Micron All Sky Survey (2MASS)
value.snippet: Mosaic images (FITS format), jpeg previews, plots, and source characterization measurements for over 500 of the largest galaxies imaged by 2MASS. Large Galaxy Atlas (using Atlas) Use Atlas to retrieve multiple FITS images covering a wide area of the sky from the 2MASS Large Galaxy Atlas.

value.name: 2MASS at IPAC
value.snippet: The 2MASS project is a collaboration between The University of Massachusetts and the Infrared Processing and Analysis Center (JPL/ Caltech). Funding is provided primarily by NASA and the NSF . The University of Massachusetts constructed and maintained the observatory facilities, and operated the survey.

value.name: 2MASS | IPAC
value.snippet: The Two Micron All-Sky Survey (2MASS) is a near-infrared digital imaging survey of the entire sky conducted by the University of Massachusetts and IPAC at 1.25, 1.65 and 2.17 microns. A pair of matched 1.3-m diameter telescopes (Arizona and Chile) completed survey operations in early 2001.

value.snippet: 2MASS J19383260+4603591 b is a gas giant exoplanet that orbits a B-type star. Its mass is 1.9 Jupiters, it takes 406 days to complete one orbit of its star, and is 0.92 AU from its star. value.name: VizieR Online Data Catalog: 2MASS All-Sky Catalog of Point Sources ...
value.snippet: The 2MASS arrays image the sky while the telescopes scan smoothly in declination at a rate of ~1' per second. The 2MASS data "tiles" are 6 deg. long in the declination direction and one camera frame (8.5') wide. The camera field-of-view shifts by ~1/6 of a frame in declination from frame-to-frame.

value.name: 2MASS J04151954−0935066 - Wikipedia
value.snippet: 2MASS J04151954−0935066 (also abbreviated to 2MASS 0415−0935) is a brown dwarf of spectral class T8, in the constellation Eridanus about 18.6 light-years from Earth. This is a reference (standard) object for the definition of the T8 spectral class.
